description: September 14, 2020: With Bulletin N. 262, the Italian Ministry of Health announced that the Italian Minister of Health, Roberto Speranza, has attended the 70th session of the WHO Regional Committee for Europe (RC70), organised by the WHO Regional Office for Europe, on September 14 and 15, 2020. Representatives of 53 countries in the WHO European Region have attended. Representatives of WHO partners such as United Nations agencies and other intergovernmental organisations and regional networks, were also present. Non-State actors (NSAs) in official relations with WHO and regional NSAs accredited by the Regional Committee, have followed the webstream and had the opportunity to submit video and written statements in advance. The key health issues and future plans have been discussed, particularly on themes regarding the response to the COVID-19 pandemic and lessons learned from the pandemic, both globally and regionally.

description: December 15, 2020: With Bulletin N. 317, the Italian Ministry of Health announced that the Italian Minister of Health attended a meeting with other European States including Belgium, France, Germany, Luxembourg, The Netherlands, Spain and Switzerland. The aim of the meeting was to discuss the vaccination campaign and the need to coordinate efforts for the safe and efficient use of the COVID-19 vaccine. During the meeting, the Ministers agreed to promote the coordination of the vaccination campaign and the rapid sharing of information between national and international authorities. Furthermore, they agreed on a fast sharing of information and experiences in the field of pharmacovigilance. The Ministers also committed to fight disinformation and fake news over the vaccination campaign. Finally, the Health Ministers agreed on the need to ensure a clear and transparent communication to the population about vaccines.

description:
The Central Commission for the navigation of the Rhine CCNR (Switzerland, France, Germany, Netherlands, Belgium) "has taken exceptional measures in relation to the COVID-19 pandemic to ensure a good performance of Rhine navigation and that the supply chain continues to operate.
The resolution adopted this Monday, 23 March 2020, will come into force immediately. In addition to infrastructure management and the validity of certificates and attestations, this resolution provides for measures ensuring free movement of crew. A crew member certificate of attestation will be provided in the annex to the resolution." " In accordance with the duration of the Governments established duration of the civil emergency, it shall remain in effect until further notice, but not later than September 23, 2020."

description: June 3, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that “France, Germany, Italy and the Netherlands are joining forces in negotiations with potential developers and manufacturers of a coronavirus vaccine. Together, the 4 countries are exploring promising vaccine initiatives and are in discussions with a number of pharmaceutical companies. They intend to have the vaccines manufactured in Europe if possible.” Therefore, the 4 countries have “agreed to form the ‘Inclusive Vaccine Alliance’. According to the alliance, one of the most urgent matters at hand is to accelerate the development process and ensure global access to an effective vaccine.”

This means that there will be no lessons at school for the majority of primary and secondary school pupils and students at schools for secondary vocational education. description: March 15, 2020: The Dutch Minister of Health Bruno Bruins and the Minister of Primary and Secondary Education Arie Slob announced additional measures in its strategy to fight coronavirus. In this regard, “primary and secondary schools, schools for secondary vocational education and childcare centres will close their doors from Monday 16 March to Monday 6 April (inclusive). Schools and childcare centres will be open for the children of parents working in crucial sectors like healthcare, the police, public transport and the fire service, so that their parents can go to work. There will be no extra charge. Teachers will organise distance learning for children at home, with priority for secondary school pupils and students in secondary vocational education preparing for their leaving examinations.” These measures will be valid until April 6, 2020.

description: March 12, 2020: The Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte and the Dutch Minister for Medical Care Bruno Bruins announced at a press conference new measures to stop the spread of coronavirus. All measures will apply until March 31, 2020 (inclusive) throughout the Netherlands. In this regard, “universities and institutions of higher professional education (HBO) are requested to offer online lectures instead of large-scale lectures.” “Primary schools, secondary schools, secondary vocational schools (MBO) and childcare centres will remain open as usual.” UPDATE: The original closure of schools only applied to higher education, this now also includes primary and secondary schools, schools for secondary vocational education and childcare centres which will close their doors from Monday 16 March to Monday 6 April (inclusive). Schools and childcare centres will remain open for the children of parents working in crucial sectors.

description:
Local Health board in Vlaardingen in the Netherlands announced that A primary school in Vlaardingen has closed its doors until after the summer holidays due to an outbreak of the coronavirus. Two parents and a student were already known to have the virus, having been tested earlier in the week. Following this, a teacher, a parent and a student have also been confirmed positive for COVID-19. Another two teachers have been tested for the virus and are waiting for the results at home.

The decision to close the school was made in accordance with the local health board. “We would have preferred to keep the school open for the last few weeks, but we think safety should come first,” said Rien Wiegeraad, director of the Un1iek school group. “But we are doing all we can to keep in touch with all our children to make sure they have the resources to follow lessons.”
date_end_spec: The policy is a one-time measure (e.g. publication of guidelines)

institution_status: Primary Schools closed/locked down

description: From 1 July, schools and childcare centres in the Netherlands will no longer offer emergency childcare for parents working in the healthcare sector. This includes hospital staff, nursing staff, carers and home carers, ambulance staff and support staff, such as cleaners at hospitals and care homes, as well as doctors and other medical staff in the armed forces. The infrastructure will remain in place so that this service can be started up again quickly if necessary.

description: August 6, 2020: The Netherlands announced that educational institutions should hold orientation activities online wherever possible. In-person activities can only take place in small groups and must be informative in nature. Study associations and student sports clubs can only hold in-person activities if these are necessary to introduce students to their chosen programme of study or sport. Such activities can only take place in small groups and must end by 22.00 at the latest. No alcohol may be consumed. The governing body of the educational institution in question and the head of the relevant safety region must give permission for such activities to take place. Student societies are not permitted to hold in-person recruitment or orientation activities.

The requests include: "From 16 December to at least 17 January inclusive, educational institutions will mainly be providing remote teaching. In secondary education, the following activities may continue on location: practical training, lessons for students with upcoming examinations, and school exams in the year of final examinations or the year before. Examinations, interim examinations and practical training may go ahead in secondary vocational education (MBO), higher professional education (HBO) and university education (WO). In all forms of education, an exception can be made when it comes to supporting vulnerable pupils and students."

description: December 14, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "the Netherlands will go into its strictest lockdown yet" from December 15, 2020 until January 19, 2021. The requests include: "From 16 December to at least 17 January inclusive, educational institutions will mainly be providing remote teaching. In secondary education, the following activities may continue on location: practical training, lessons for students with upcoming examinations, and school exams in the year of final examinations or the year before. Examinations, interim examinations and practical training may go ahead in secondary vocational education (MBO), higher professional education (HBO) and university education (WO). In all forms of education, an exception can be made when it comes to supporting vulnerable pupils and students." UPDATE: January 12, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that the country will remain in lockdown until at least February 9, 2021. The requests include: "Until at least 8 February, educational institutions will provide most teaching remotely. Secondary schools can offer practical training, school exams for pupils in the upper years and lessons for pupils with upcoming final exams on site." "As a precaution, and where possible, secondary school pupils being taught at school should stay 1.5 metres apart." "Secondary vocational schools (MBO), higher professional education institutions (HBO) and universities can offer exams and practical training on site. All educational institutions can make exceptions to provide support to vulnerable children or students."

UPDATE: June 18, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "step 4 of the reopening plan can be taken and that more restrictions than planned can be relaxed" from June 26, 2021. It will continue to apply only in situations where staying 1.5 apart is impossible,” thus changing this policy for primary schools.

description: February 5, 2021: The Ministry of Health, Welfare and Sport of the Netherlands announced that AstraZeneca vaccine will be given from February 15, 2021. It will be given to people aged 60-64 and to specific medical risk groups. UPDATE: March 14, 2021: In the Netherlands, due to cases of side effects with the AstraZeneca vaccine, the Dutch Medicines Authority (MEB) has advised, as a precautionary measure and pending further investigation, to pause the administration of the AstraZeneca corona vaccine. Minister Hugo de Jonge (VWS) takes over the advice. Based on the precautionary principle, it has been decided not to use AstraZeneca for the next two weeks (until March 28, 2021), the minister reports in a letter to the House of Representatives.

description: March 17, 2020: The Netherlands are advising all Dutch people not to travel abroad in the coming period unless absolutely essential, thus marking travel advice for all countries at ‘orange’: travel only if absolutely essential. UPDATE: June 15, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands continues to advise against travels abroad. Most countries are classified as "orange", which means that only essential travels are recommended, but there are exceptions made for certain countries in Europe. The following European countries have ben downgraded from orange to yellow: Belgium, Bulgaria, Croatia, the Czech Republic, Estonia, France, Germany, Iceland, Italy, Latvia, Liechtenstein, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Poland, Portugal and Switzerland. Travel to yellow countries is not adviced against because the risk to health there is comparable to that in the Netherlands.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
target_geog_level: All countries
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health

description: As of 15 June 2020, Dutch government eases the travelling within Europe. Travel advisories for several European countries will be changed from orange to yellow. That means that the risk to health in these countries is comparable to that in the Netherlands and that these countries are happy to receive Dutch tourists. Other countries, for instance France and Spain, still need to make an official decision on whether or not Dutch tourists are welcome this summer. UPDATE: July 22, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands's advise not to travel abroad has been expanded. The travel advisory for Croatia is changed from yellow to orange, meaning that Dutch people should only travel there if absolutely necessary. The exceptions for the following European countries are still in place: Belgium, Bulgaria, the Czech Republic, Estonia, France, Germany, Iceland, Italy, Latvia, Liechtenstein, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Poland, Portugal and Switzerland. For remaining countries, the travel advice is still orange.

description:
The Netherlands shut its borders to people from Serbia and Montenegro again on Wednesday, a week after opening them, citing a rapid rise in coronavirus infections in both countries.

Travellers from Serbia and Montenegro regained access to the Netherlands on July 1 when the Dutch, following European Union guidelines, reopened their borders to a list of 14 countries outside the bloc.

But the government said a rise in coronavirus infections in Serbia and Montenegro had forced it to take those countries off the list again, and that Dutch travellers should only visit them if absolutely necessary.

description: July 22, 2020: The Dutch Ministry of Foreign Affairs tightened its travel advice or Croatia due to increasing coronavirus infections in the country. A code orange warning now applies to Croatia, meaning that Dutch are urged to only go there if absolutely necessary. UPDATE: July 28, 2020: The Dutch government’s travel advice for the Barcelona metropolitan area and Segrià region has been changed to code orange, meaning all but essential travel to the area should be avoided. Travellers returning from both regions are urged to self-isolate for 14 days. The exceptions for the following European countries are still in place: Belgium, Bulgaria, Croatia, the Czech Republic, Estonia, France, Germany, Iceland, Italy, Latvia, Liechtenstein, Lithuania, Luxembourg, Poland, Portugal and Switzerland. description:
The Netherlands shut its borders to people from Serbia and Montenegro again on Wednesday, a week after opening them, citing a rapid rise in coronavirus infections in both countries.

Travellers from Serbia and Montenegro regained access to the Netherlands on July 1 when the Dutch, following European Union guidelines, reopened their borders to a list of 14 countries outside the bloc.

But the government said a rise in coronavirus infections in Serbia and Montenegro had forced it to take those countries off the list again, and that Dutch travellers should only visit them if absolutely necessary. UPDATE: From 5 August 2020, the Netherlands amends travel restrictions, reinstating the entry ban for Algeria.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date

description:
February 3, 2021: The Netherlands has tightened international entry restrictions. International travelers arriving via air or sea must undergo a COVID-19 rapid antigen test no more than four hours prior to boarding their flight or ferry. Transit passengers are also subject to this requirement. Air crews must undergo a rapid antigen test upon disembarking. Ship crews may undergo a rapid antigen test up to 24 hours prior to departure.

Rapid antigen tests are required in addition to negative COVID-19 polymerase chain reaction (PCR) test results, which are required for most travelers arriving by air, sea, or land; the test must be taken no more than 72 hours prior to departure. All arrivals, including Dutch nationals, must also fill out a negative test declaration form prior to travel. Additionally, all travelers must self-isolate for 10 days on arrival. These measures do not apply to individuals arriving from China, the Dutch Caribbean Territories, Australia, Japan, New Zealand, Rwanda, Singapore, South Korea, and Thailand; additional exceptions are possible for individuals with an essential function or need, such as health workers, on-duty security forces, freight workers, and diplomats.
date_end_spec: The policy’s end date is unknown or unreported

description: November 3, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced a temporary tightening of the partial lockdown introduced on October 14, 2020. From 10pm on November 4, 2020 up to and including November 18, 2020, the following measures that concern travel abroad will apply: "Avoid travelling abroad and do not book trips abroad until mid-January, unless your journey is essential. Holidays and family visits are non-essential travel." UPDATE: March 8, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that it "has made minor adjustments to the current measures and is looking ahead. There may be more scope for easing restrictions as of 31 March." Starting from now, the requests include: "Stay in the Netherlands. Do not travel abroad in the period up to and including 15 April. Do no travel outside the Netherlands unless absolutely necessary. At the next press conference, on 23 March, the government will announce a new travel advisory for the period after 15 April."
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
target_geog_level: All countries
enforcer: National Government

description: November 3, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced a temporary tightening of the partial lockdown introduced on October 14, 2020. From 10pm on November 4, 2020 up to and including November 18, 2020, the following measures that concern travel abroad will apply: "Avoid travelling abroad and do not book trips abroad until mid-January, unless your journey is essential. Holidays and family visits are non-essential travel." UPDATE: March 23, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "the third wave is becoming apparent, so the measures currently in place are going to be extended." In this regard, "the advice not to travel abroad will apply up to and including Saturday 15 May. Stay in the Netherlands. Do not travel abroad, unless it is absolutely essential. This also applies to the May holidays. In April the government and the travel and passenger transport industries will start pilot projects involving trips abroad, which should give insight into how we will be able to holiday abroad safely and responsibly in the future."

description: March 25, 2021: The Netherlands’ government has decided to extend the advice against travelling abroad for its citizens, until May 15, after taking into account the current infection rate of the Coronavirus in foreign countries. description: April 26, 2021: The Dutch Minister of Infrastructure and Water Management Cora van Nieuwenhuizen, at the direction of Dutch Health Minister Hugo de Jonge and following the urgent advice of the National Institute for Public Health and the Environment (RIVM), introduced a ban on all incoming passenger flights from India from April 26, 2021 at 6pm. “Passenger flights from India will be banned until at least 1 May 2021 at 00.01. The ban does not apply to cargo flights and flights carrying medical personnel.” This was decided by the Dutch government.

description: June 15, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands designates the UK, Bangladesh, Myanmar and Nepal as very high risk as of June 15, 2021. All travelers that arrive from these countries need to present either a negative result from a COVID-19 PCR test taken no more than 24 hours prior to boarding transport or a negative result from a PCR test taken no more than 72 hours prior to arrival in the Netherlands coupled with a negative rapid antigen COVID-19 test taken no more than 24 hours prior to boarding. These travelers will also need to self-isolate for 10 days on arrival; this can be shortened by taking a COVID-19 test on or after day five of the self-isolation period. Vaccinated passengers are also subject to this requirement. Exceptions are possible for individuals with an essential function or need, such as cross-border workers, health workers, on-duty security forces, freight workers, and diplomats.
date_end_spec: The policy’s end date is unknown or unreported
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries

description: Effective July 27, 2021, the Netherlands will not designate EU countries as ‘orange’ solely on the basis of the number of coronavirus infections there. An EU country can still be designated as orange, but only if a new variant of concern is present there. This effectively means that the government is no longer advising against travel to any EU countries, which are all to be designated as either yellow or green.

description: From August 8, 2021, the Netherlands requires proof of a test or vaccination certificate when returning from a country outside of Europe. It is also mandatory for those who come from a safe country. This applies to yellow and orange countries. You can also take a PCR test no more than 48 hours before departure. An antigen test can be done for up to 24 hours. And also for travelers returning from a country outside of Europe, it is strongly recommended to take a free corona test at GGD or self-test on the 2nd and 5th day after arrival.

description: November 17, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that the partial lockdown introduced on October 14, 2020 will remain in place starting from November 19, 2020. In this regard, the government reminded citizens of the importance of "keeping to the basic rules": "Following the basic rules remains vital in order to reduce the number of infections. Anyone who has symptoms, even mild symptoms, should stay at home and get tested as soon as possible. Anyone who is infected should ask others to do shopping and other tasks for them, so they can stay at home. Everyone should stay 1.5 metres apart and leave if places become too busy. You are strongly advised to wear a face mask in indoor public spaces." UPDATE: December 8, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "it is extra important that everyone keeps following the basic rules during the festive season. This means staying 1.5 metres away from people who do not live with you – even at the dinner table and during celebrations. Hold your festivities in the largest possible space so that it’s easier to maintain a safe distance. Wash your hands often, including when you arrive somewhere and before eating. And if you have symptoms, no matter how mild, stay at home and get tested. Do not go out and do not receive visitors. If you are infected, ask other people to do your shopping and other errands for you. Following the basic rules is also important in the run-up to the holidays. Plan what you need to buy beforehand, shop in the mornings or on weekdays, and go alone. Local authorities and shop managers are taking measures to prevent crowds and help people comply with the rules."

description: February 2, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands has "decided to extend the current lockdown." Therefore, it announced: "The roadmap of measures to combat the spread of coronavirus has been updated. The government will use this updated roadmap in the future, when deciding to either ease or tighten measures. The idea behind the roadmap is to make it clear what measures are needed if infections, pressure on the healthcare system and hospital admissions increase, as well as which measures might be relaxed if the situation changes for the better. Whatever the case, it is vital that any easing of measures is done gradually and with due care. On the other hand, new measures must be introduced quickly. The roadmap will be regularly updated to reflect the latest knowledge on the virus and the impact of measures."

description: November 17, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that the partial lockdown introduced on October 14, 2020 will remain in place starting from November 19, 2020. In this regard, the government reminded citizens of the importance of "keeping to the basic rules": "Following the basic rules remains vital in order to reduce the number of infections. Anyone who has symptoms, even mild symptoms, should stay at home and get tested as soon as possible. Anyone who is infected should ask others to do shopping and other tasks for them, so they can stay at home. Everyone should stay 1.5 metres apart and leave if places become too busy. You are strongly advised to wear a face mask in indoor public spaces." UPDATE: February 23, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that the lockdown "will remain in force at least up to and including" March 15, 2021. The requests include: "pay extra attention to following the basic rules. That includes the hygiene rules, such as frequent hand-washing, sneezing into your elbow and wearing a face mask wherever required. It also means staying 1.5 metres away from others and avoiding busy places. It’s also essential – now more than ever – that you get tested and stay at home, even if you experience only mild symptoms."

For instance, by limiting the number of people allowed in the shop at the same time.” “Shops and markets must close […] if the relevant hygiene measures are not complied with sufficiently or if people are not keeping a good distance from others (1.5 metres).” UPDATE: March 31, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands prolonged all previous measures, including hygiene and social distancing requirements for shops and markets, until April 28, 2020 (inclusive).

description: March 23, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands introduced additional measures to combat the coronavirus outbreak. In this regard, “establishments such as holiday parks must put measures in place so that people keep a distance of 1.5 metres from each other.” “Local authorities may order these locations to close” “if the relevant hygiene measures are not complied with sufficiently, if people are not keeping a good distance from others (1.5 metres) or if there is a risk of either of these situations occurring.” This measure will be reassessed by April 6, 2020 at the latest. UPDATE: March 31, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands prolonged all previous measures, including restrictions for holiday parks, until April 28, 2020 (inclusive).

description: March 23, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands introduced additional measures to combat the coronavirus outbreak. In this regard, “all those in contact-based roles must stop performing their jobs, unless it is possible to maintain a distance of 1.5 metres from clients at all times. This includes masseurs, hairdressers, nail stylists, escorts and driving instructors. An exception has been made for those providing treatment in medical or paramedical roles, but only if there is a specific medical reason and the relevant hygiene measures are taken.” Contact-based professionals “are urged to work via video calls wherever possible.” This measure will be reassessed by April 6, 2020 at the latest. UPDATE: March 31, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands prolonged all previous measures, including restrictions for contact-based professionals, until April 28, 2020 (inclusive).

description: May 6, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "from Monday 11 May we can allow one another a little more freedom, while keeping coronavirus under control." In this regard, "Most people in contact-based roles will be allowed to perform their jobs again. This includes driving instructors, medical and paramedical professionals (dieticians, massage therapists, occupational therapists, prosthodontists, etc.), hair and beauty professionals (hairdressers, beauticians, pedicurists, etc.) and alternative medicine practitioners (acupuncturists, homeopaths, etc.). They should stay 1.5 metres apart from their clients wherever possible. They should see clients by appointment only and assess possible health risks beforehand together with the client."

description: May 19, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that more measures will be relaxed from June 1, 2020. In this regard, the following measure applies: “Restaurants, bars and cafés can open under the following conditions: a maximum of 30 guests (so not counting staff); people must make a reservation; everyone must stay 1.5 metres apart (except people who live together); the business must assess possible health risks beforehand together with the customer. There is no maximum number of people for outdoor seating areas, but all guests must sit at tables and people who do not live together must stay 1.5 metres apart.” “Developments permitting, more measures will be relaxed on 1 July.”

description: September 28, 2020: Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte and Minister of Health, Welfare and Sport Hugo de Jonge announced at a national press conference new measures that will come into effect on September 29, 2020 at 6pm and will be in force for at least the next 3 weeks. These measures include: "Those in contact-based professions must ask their customers to provide their contact details, in the same way that restaurants, bars and cafés do." "This requirement does not apply to professions where providing contact details would hinder the performance of services or endanger the safety and wellbeing of those involved, such as care providers, enforcement officers and investigating officers."

description: May 11, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the second step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on May 19, 2021. In this regard, “indoor locations for artistic and cultural activities will reopen. People will be able to take music, dance or theatre lessons again. Teachers can give lessons to individuals or groups of 2. Larger group lessons are not allowed, except for children under 18. A maximum of 30 people applies per space. People must stay 1.5 metres apart, except when the nature of the activity makes this impossible. An example of this is dancing. No audiences are allowed. Reservations and a health check are mandatory. A face mask must be worn indoors, unless the nature of the activity makes it necessary to remove it during practice and rehearsal.”

In this regard, “all shops may admit customers without an appointment. Certain conditions still apply, such as a limit on the number of shoppers allowed inside at the same time. It’s still important to avoid busy places, so go to the shops at quiet times, such as early in the morning. And go alone if possible. Shops selling non-essential goods, such as clothes shops, can be open between 6:00 and 20:00. description: May 28, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the third step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on June 5, 2021. In this regard, “establishments serving food and drink can be open from 06.00 to 22.00. Everyone must have an assigned seat at a table. Sitting at the bar is not permitted. A maximum of 4 people are allowed to sit at a table and they must be seated 1.5 metres apart. This does not apply to children under the age of 13 or people who are part of the same household. A maximum of 50 people applies, excluding staff. The same maximum applies to outdoor seating areas. Restaurants and cafés can serve dinner in a maximum of two sittings per table per evening. Self-service is not allowed. Entertainment such as live performances or television screens showing sporting events are also not permitted. A reservation, health check and assigned seat are mandatory.”

description: May 28, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the third step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on June 5, 2021. In this regard, “indoor spaces at amusement parks, nature parks and zoos may reopen. These include, for example, reptile houses and covered attractions. Casinos, play and recreational facilities (for example, laser gaming venues), saunas and spas may also reopen. The maximum number of visitors permitted will be either one person per 10 square metres or up to 50 people in one space, 1.5 metres apart, depending on the nature of the activity, i.e. whether visitors move around or are mainly seated. Reservations, registration and a health check are mandatory. Reservations can be made for up to 4 people. This limit does not apply to children and people who are part of the same household. When indoors visitors must wear a face mask.”

description: May 28, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the third step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on June 5, 2021. In this regard, “the government has decided to introduce coronavirus entry passes as part of step 3 of the reopening plan. Establishments serving food and drink, cultural venues and organisers of professional sporting competitions can choose to make use of this system. This can help them ensure that they can safely host more people. Venues such as theatres or restaurants that do not use the system can host a maximum of 50 people. If they opt to use the system, they can host as many people as they can accommodate if people are 1.5 metres from one another while seated. Events where guests have an assigned seat, whether indoor or outdoors, are also allowed again. However, these events must take account of local rules and requirements, such as permits.” "The fourth step of the reopening plan is now planned for 30 June."

description: September 18, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced new regional measures to control the spread of coronavirus which will come into effect at 6pm on September 20, 2020. “The measures have been coordinated closely with 6 safety regions (Amsterdam-Amstelland, Rotterdam-Rijnmond, Haaglanden, Utrecht, Kennemerland and Hollands Midden) and are based on urgent recommendations by the Outbreak Management Team.” In all six regions, “groups of more than 50 people are banned. This means, for instance, no parties, receptions or outings for groups of more than 50 people. This restriction applies both indoors and outdoors. There are some exceptions, such as demonstrations, religious gatherings, funerals, and dance and theatre.“ “Organisers of gatherings of more than 50 people must notify the authorities beforehand. […] The notification requirement does not apply to, for instance, establishments with a catering licence, religious gatherings, shops and markets, libraries, cultural venues and similar locations where there is a continuous coming and going of visitors.”

In this regard, “the government strongly and urgently advises people to limit the number of guests they receive at home to a maximum of six (excluding children under 13). This includes both indoors and in outdoor spaces like gardens. Guests should also be asked whether they have any symptoms and if so, they should not attend. It goes without saying that people should always stay 1.5 metres away from each other.” UPDATE: September 28, 2020: Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte and Minister of Health, Welfare and Sport Hugo de Jonge announced that the number of guests that can be received at home, in the garden or on the balcony has been lowered, thus ending this policy.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health

description: September 28, 2020: Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte and Minister of Health, Welfare and Sport Hugo de Jonge announced at a national press conference new measures that will come into effect on September 29, 2020 at 6pm and will be in force for at least the next 3 weeks. These measures include: "The number of people in 1 room is limited to 30 people. This includes children under 13 but excludes staff." "Numbers for outdoor activities where there is no continuous flow of people are limited to 40." These measures affect weddings, setting a limit of 30 people (indoors) or 40 people (outdoors) (including children but excluding staff).
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries

description: September 18, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced new regional measures to control the spread of coronavirus which will come into effect at 6pm on September 20, 2020. “The measures have been coordinated closely with 6 safety regions (Amsterdam-Amstelland, Rotterdam-Rijnmond, Haaglanden, Utrecht, Kennemerland and Hollands Midden) and are based on urgent recommendations by the Outbreak Management Team.” In all six regions, “groups of more than 50 people are banned. This means, for instance, no parties, receptions or outings for groups of more than 50 people. This restriction applies both indoors and outdoors. There are some exceptions, such as demonstrations, religious gatherings, funerals, and dance and theatre.“ “Organisers of gatherings of more than 50 people must notify the authorities beforehand. […] The notification requirement does not apply to, for instance, establishments with a catering licence, religious gatherings, shops and markets, libraries, cultural venues and similar locations where there is a continuous coming and going of visitors.” UPDATE: October 13, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced a partial lockdown starting from 10pm on October 14, 2020. In this regard, measures that concern events changed at national level, ending this policy.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
target_geog_level: One or more geographical or administrative units (other than provincial or city level units) within one or more countries
target_other: Amsterdam-Amstelland (North Holland and South Holland); Rotterdam-Rijnmond (South Holland); Haaglanden (South Holland); Utrecht (Utrecht); Kennemerland (North Holland); Hollands Midden (South Holland)

description: October 13, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced a partial lockdown starting from 10pm on October 14, 2020. In this regard, measures that concern sport include: “Taking part in individual sports or in team sports with no more than 4 people in total is allowed for anyone aged 18 if they keep a distance of 1.5 metres. Matches and competitions are not permitted. Exceptions are: elite athletes with a status at assigned locations (such as Papendal); footballers (incl. support staff in a ‘bubble’) in the Eredivisie and Eerste Divisie. Taking part in team sports, including matches and competitions with teams within their own club, is allowed for children under 18. In addition to sports canteens and clubhouses, showers and changing rooms will also remain closed.”

UPDATE: July 9, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that extra measures are necessary during summer. In this regard, concerning "special events", "funerals: there is no maximum group size. Full capacity is permitted, with 1.5-metre distancing." This provision will take effect from 6am on July 10, 2021 and remain in place until August 13, 2021.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health,Ministry/Department of Justice

description: March 13, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that the Custodial Institutions Agency, based on the advice of the National Institute for Public Health and the Environment, has decided that “all visits to prisoners in custodial institutions will be suspended”. “In order for contact to be maintained as much as possible, opportunities for telephone and – wherever possible – Skype contact will be expanded. The only visits that will be allowed are those that are essential to the course of justice, such as lawyer visits (and which cannot be replaced by the use of digital aids). Young people in young-offenders institutions may continue to receive visits from their parents or legal guardians.” These measures will apply from March 14 until at least March 31, 2020.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries

description: March 13, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that the Custodial Institutions Agency, based on the advice of the National Institute for Public Health and the Environment, has decided that “all visits to prisoners in custodial institutions will be suspended”. “In order for contact to be maintained as much as possible, opportunities for telephone and – wherever possible – Skype contact will be expanded. The only visits that will be allowed are those that are essential to the course of justice, such as lawyer visits (and which cannot be replaced by the use of digital aids). Young people in young-offenders institutions may continue to receive visits from their parents or legal guardians.” These measures will apply from March 14 until at least March 31, 2020. UPDATE: April 2, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that the Custodial Institutions Agency has extended corona measures until April 28, 2020. “These measures concern postponing visits and prison leave for detainees in in prisons and forensic care facilities, as well as reducing their trips to and from court. In addition, the visiting policy for young offenders institutions will be made stricter to prevent the spread of coronavirus. This means that detained youth are also no longer able to receive visitors as of 1 April.” As a replacement, “in order to allow detainees to remain in touch with their loved ones, which is necessary for their reintegration, they are being given more opportunities for telephoning and can now use Skype.”
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date

UPDATE: March 31, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands prolonged all previous measures, including restrictions for camp sites, parks, nature conservation areas and beaches, until April 28, 2020 (inclusive).
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart at Other public outdoor spaces
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health,Ministry/Department of Justice,Other (Please specify in the text box)

description: March 23, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands introduced additional measures to combat the coronavirus outbreak. In this regard, it is recommended to “always keep a good distance from other people (at least 1.5 metres) and avoid all social activities and groups of people.” This measure will be reassessed by April 6, 2020 at the latest. UPDATE: March 31, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands prolonged all previous measures, recommending to “always keep a good distance from other people” until April 28, 2020 (inclusive).
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date

description: March 19, 2020: The Dutch Minister of Health Hugo de Jonge (Netherlands) has announced that from March 20, 2020 "nursing homes and small-scale residential accommodation for the elderly will be closed to visitors and anyone not involved in the provision of basic care". "Institutions can make an exception to the ‘no visitors’ rule specifically when a resident is dying." This measure will apply nationwide until at least April 6, 2020 (inclusive). UPDATE: March 31, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands is prolonging all previous measures until April 28, 2020 (inclusive).
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Restrictions on visiting nursing homes/long term care facilities

description: May 6, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "from Monday 11 May we can allow one another a little more freedom, while keeping coronavirus under control." In this regard, "Most people in contact-based roles will be allowed to perform their jobs again. This includes driving instructors, medical and paramedical professionals (dieticians, massage therapists, occupational therapists, prosthodontists, etc.), hair and beauty professionals (hairdressers, beauticians, pedicurists, etc.) and alternative medicine practitioners (acupuncturists, homeopaths, etc.). They should stay 1.5 metres apart from their clients wherever possible. They should see clients by appointment only and assess possible health risks beforehand together with the client."

description: June 1, 2020: The local council of Amsterdam (the Netherlands) may close off streets to cars in an effort to allow crisis-hit bar owners to have a terrace, provided they come up with a plan that guarantees safe passage for passers-by and other traffic. Bar and restaurant owners will also be allowed more space in public places such as squares, bridges, boats and car parks under the new rules. They will also be allowed to use heaters and parasols so the terraces can be used in all weathers. The decision to close off a road to cars to increase seating capacity will only be taken ‘if accessibility of facilities and the general traffic flow allow’ and ‘only if enough space remains for passers-by and other traffic streams’. The main terrace rules include a 1.5 metre safe distance ‘from mouth to mouth’, a maximum of four people to a table, and enough distance between passers-by and customers. The extended or new terraces must be licenced and will not be taxed until July 1, 2020. These regulations will be valid till October 31, 2020.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart at Restaurants
target_geog_level: One or more cities within one or more countries
enforcer: Provincial/State Government

description: May 19, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that more measures will be relaxed from June 1, 2020. In this regard, the following measure applies: “Use public transport for essential travel only. From 1 June passengers aged 13 and over will be required to wear a non-medical face mask on trams, buses, water buses, metros and trains. In stations, on platforms and at bus and tram stops face masks are not required, but people must stay 1.5 metres away from others. Passengers who do not wear a face mask after 1 June can be fined €95.”

description: August 5, 2020: The Netherlands announced that face masks will be mandatory for everyone of the age 13 and above in following parts of Amsterdam: Nieuwendijk and Kalverstraat: on the street and inside shops during day and night (24/7); Red Light District (northern area, excluding Damstraat): on the street and inside shops during day and night (24/7); Plein '40-'45 market: during the street market’s opening hours; Albert Cuypstraat market: on the street and inside shops during the street market’s opening hours. This measure will apply until August 31, 2020.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
target_geog_level: One or more cities within one or more countries
enforcer: Ministry/Department of Health

description: July 30, 2020: The Rotterdam-Rijnmond Security Region announced that everyone aged 13 and older will be required to wear a face mask beginning on August 5, 2020. Central shopping districts in Rotterdam, including Coolsingel, Lijnbaan, Meent and Nieuwe Binnenwegplein. Also included are the covered shopping centers Alexandrium and Zuidplein, and the markets at Afrikaanderplein, De Binnenrotte, and Visserijplein. The officials were undecided about the covered shopping centers De Binnenhof and Keizerswaard. This measure will apply until August 31, 2020.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_text: Mandatory use of face masks in certain areas in cities
target_geog_level: One or more cities within one or more countries
target_who_gen: People of a certain age (please note age range in the text entry)
enforcer: Municipal Government

description: June 24, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that “A new phase is beginning and we are moving from an intelligent lockdown to less restrictive rules”. In this regard, concerning general rules outdoors, the following measure applies from July 1, 2020: (private) “In shops, museums, libraries and other settings where visitors move through the space, the rule is that people must stay 1.5 metres apart. It is up to locations to make sure people follow this rule. Here, no maximum number of people applies.” UPDATE: September 1, 2020: Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte and Health Minister Hugo de Jonge "held a press conference to update the public on the coronavirus pandemic". In this regard, it was decided that there will be "no easing of measures at present". This policy is thus extended until further reevaluation.

description: September 28, 2020: Dutch Prime Minister Mark Rutte and Minister of Health, Welfare and Sport Hugo de Jonge announced at a national press conference new measures to reduce contact between people. These measures will come into effect on September 29, 2020 at 6pm and will be in force for at least the next 3 weeks. "They aim to reduce the risk of overcrowding and limit the amount of people coming into contact with one another in social settings, without placing society and the economy into lockdown."

description: December 1, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that “as of 1 December 2020, everyone aged 13 and over must wear a face mask in settings in which they are mandatory,” namely “all indoor public spaces and covered areas. This includes educational institutions, public transport and locations where contact-based professions are carried out, as well as shops, town halls and train stations.” “Always stay 1.5 metres away from other people, even if you are wearing a face mask.” “Keep your mask on wherever it is mandatory to do so, even if there are no other people around.” “Use face masks made for use by the general public. The use of transparent face shields instead of a face mask is not permitted.” “You can remove your face mask indoors once you are seated in an assigned seat, such as in a theatre. When you leave your seat, you must put your mask back on. This does not apply to public transport; you must wear your mask at all times while travelling by train, bus, tram or metro.” “Face masks are not mandatory in private buildings that are not freely accessible to the public.” “If you do not wear a face mask in a place where you must wear one, you may be fined.”
date_end_spec: The policy’s end date is unknown or unreported
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries
compliance: Mandatory with Fines,Mandatory with Exceptions (Please list exceptions in the text entry)
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health

description: October 13, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced a partial lockdown (starting from 10pm on October 14, 2020). description: February 2, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands has "decided to extend the current lockdown." Therefore, the following measures apply from now until at least March 2, 2021 inclusive: (Click and collect) "As of 10 February, non-essential shops will be allowed to offer their customers the option of collecting their order in person. Customers should order their goods (online or by phone) at least 4 hours in advance and make an appointment to collect them in or outside the shop. The basic rules apply at all times: stay 1.5 metres apart, follow the basic hygiene measures and stay home if you have symptoms of COVID-19."
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date

description: March 8, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that it "has made minor adjustments to the current measures and is looking ahead. There may be more scope for easing restrictions as of 31 March." Starting from March 16, 2021, the requests include: "Shops will be allowed to admit 2 customers per floor or 1 customer per 25 square metres, up to a maximum of 50 customers at a time, if the shop is big enough. Everyone must stay 1.5 metres apart. The rule that appointments must be made at least 4 hours in advance still applies and each customer slot must be a minimum of 10 minutes." UPDATE: March 23, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that all current measures will apply up to and including April 20, 2021. In this regard, concerning "locations that are (partially) open", the following measures continue to apply: "Shops selling essential items like food and drink, as well as chemists [are open]. Shops can offer a ‘click and collect’ service and shopping by appointment is also possible."

description: February 23, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that the lockdown "will remain in force at least up to and including" March 15, 2021. The requests include: "From 1 March, [...] Higher professional education institutions (HBO) and universities can offer exams and practical training on site". "All educational institutions can make exceptions to provide support to vulnerable [...] students". UPDATE: March 23, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced an extension of this measure until April 26, 2021 (exclusive). In this regard, "Higher professional education institutions (HBO) and universities are offering remote and online learning". "Students can attend their [...] university in person for practical training, tests and exams. Vulnerable [...] students can also be offered support on site at their school [or] institution". "The government wants higher education students to be able to attend in-person classes again without delay. This will be possible from 26 April at the earliest".

description: March 23, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced an extension of this measure until April 26, 2021 (exclusive). In this regard, "Secondary schools are open. These schools are mainly offering remote and online learning to their pupils. Each pupil attends in-person lessons at least 1 day per week". UPDATE: April 20, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the first step of its staggered reopening plan. In this regard, “as of Monday 26 April, [...] Secondary schools are open. "Pupils [...] can attend their school [...] in person for practical training, tests and exams". "Vulnerable pupils and students can also be offered support on site at their school". description: April 20, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the first step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on April 28, 2021. In this regard, “all shops may admit customers without an appointment. Certain conditions still apply, such as a limit on the number of shoppers allowed inside at the same time. It’s still important to avoid busy places, so go to the shops at quiet times, such as early in the morning. And go alone if possible. Shops selling non-essential goods, such as clothes shops, can be open between 6:00 and 20:00. […] Wearing a face mask in shops is still compulsory.” The second step of the reopening plan is planned for May 11, 2021, making this policy valid at least until May 10, 2021.

description: April 20, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the first step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on April 28, 2021. In this regard, “outdoor seating areas at restaurants and cafés may be open from 12:00 to 18:00, under certain conditions. Each establishment may have a maximum of 50 guests. Each guest must be assigned a seat. Self-service is not allowed. No more than 2 people may be seated at a table, sitting 1.5 metres apart. However, this limit does not apply if everyone at the table is part of the same household or if the party includes children under 13. Visitors can go indoors only to pay, use the cloakroom or go to the toilet. Face masks must be worn indoors.” The second step of the reopening plan is planned for May 11, 2021, making this policy valid at least until May 10, 2021.

description: May 11, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the second step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on May 19, 2021. In this regard, “indoor sports facilities like fitness centres and swimming pools may reopen, subject to conditions. A maximum of 30 people applies per space and people must stay 1.5 metres apart. People may only exercise or do sports individually or in groups of 2, with an instructor, and they must stay 1.5 metres apart. Larger group lessons are not allowed, except for children under 18. Competitions and spectators are not allowed. Changing rooms must not be used, except at swimming pools. Reservations and a health check are mandatory. A face mask must be worn indoors, except during the sports activity.” "The third step of the reopening plan will not be taken until 9 June at the earliest."

description: May 11, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the second step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on May 19, 2021. In this regard, “amusement parks, nature parks, zoos and petting farms will reopen, subject to conditions. This also applies to facilities for outdoor play and recreation, such as miniature golf, climbing parks and playgrounds. The number of visitors is limited to one per 10 square metres and all visitors must stay 1.5 metres apart. Reservations and a health check are mandatory. description: May 11, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the second step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on May 19, 2021. In this regard, “indoor locations for artistic and cultural activities will reopen. People will be able to take music, dance or theatre lessons again. Teachers can give lessons to individuals or groups of 2. Larger group lessons are not allowed, except for children under 18. A maximum of 30 people applies per space. People must stay 1.5 metres apart, except when the nature of the activity makes this impossible. An example of this is dancing. No audiences are allowed. Reservations and a health check are mandatory. A face mask must be worn indoors, unless the nature of the activity makes it necessary to remove it during practice and rehearsal.”
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart at Commercial Businesses
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries
compliance: Mandatory with Exceptions (Please list exceptions in the text entry)
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health,Ministry/Department of Justice

description: April 20, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the first step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on April 28, 2021. In this regard, “all shops may admit customers without an appointment. Certain conditions still apply, such as a limit on the number of shoppers allowed inside at the same time. It’s still important to avoid busy places, so go to the shops at quiet times, such as early in the morning. And go alone if possible. Shops selling non-essential goods, such as clothes shops, can be open between 6:00 and 20:00. […] Wearing a face mask in shops is still compulsory.” The second step of the reopening plan is planned for May 11, 2021, making this policy valid at least until May 10, 2021. UPDATE: May 11, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the second step of its staggered reopening plan. All measures not included in this second step will continue to apply until the announcement of the third step on June 9, 2021.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health,Ministry/Department of Justice

description: April 20, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the first step of its staggered reopening plan. In this regard, “as of Monday 26 April, students at universities and HBO institutions will again be able to attend classes at their educational institution". "Higher professional education institutions (HBO) and universities are partially open. They are still mainly offering remote and online learning. Each student can attend in-person classes approximately one day per week". "Students can attend their [...] university in person for practical training, tests and exams. Vulnerable [...] students can also be offered support on site at their school [or] institution". The second step of the reopening plan will be announced on May 11, 2021. UPDATE: May 11, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the second step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on May 19, 2021. All measures not included in this second step will continue to apply until the announcement of the third step on June 1, 2021. No relaxations are announced for "higher professional education institutions (HBO) and universities", thus confirming this policy until further reevaluation.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart at Higher education institutions (i.e. degree granting institutions)
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health,Ministry/Department of Justice,Ministry/Department of Education

description: January 20, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced stricter lockdown measures following the insurgence of the UK variant of coronavirus and "other variants of the virus that are sparking concern." "New measures are needed in order to get these new variants under control." The requests, which apply until at least February 9, 2021, include: "Visit no more than 1 other household per day." UPDATE: May 11, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the second step of its staggered reopening plan. All measures not included in this second step will continue to apply until the announcement of the third step on June 9, 2021. Thus, the following request continues to be valid: “Visit no more than 1 other household per day.”

description: May 28, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the third step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on June 5, 2021. In this regard, “establishments serving food and drink can be open from 06.00 to 22.00. Everyone must have an assigned seat at a table. Sitting at the bar is not permitted. A maximum of 4 people are allowed to sit at a table and they must be seated 1.5 metres apart. This does not apply to children under the age of 13 or people who are part of the same household. A maximum of 50 people applies, excluding staff. The same maximum applies to outdoor seating areas. Restaurants and cafés can serve dinner in a maximum of two sittings per table per evening. Self-service is not allowed. Entertainment such as live performances or television screens showing sporting events are also not permitted. A reservation, health check and assigned seat are mandatory.”
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart at Restaurants
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health,Ministry/Department of Justice

description: May 28, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the third step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on June 5, 2021. In this regard, “indoor spaces at amusement parks, nature parks and zoos may reopen. These include, for example, reptile houses and covered attractions. Casinos, play and recreational facilities (for example, laser gaming venues), saunas and spas may also reopen. The maximum number of visitors permitted will be either one person per 10 square metres or up to 50 people in one space, 1.5 metres apart, depending on the nature of the activity, i.e. whether visitors move around or are mainly seated. Reservations, registration and a health check are mandatory. Reservations can be made for up to 4 people. This limit does not apply to children and people who are part of the same household. When indoors visitors must wear a face mask.”
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart at Commercial Businesses

description: May 28, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the third step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on June 5, 2021. In this regard, “the government has decided to introduce coronavirus entry passes as part of step 3 of the reopening plan. Establishments serving food and drink, cultural venues and organisers of professional sporting competitions can choose to make use of this system. This can help them ensure that they can safely host more people. Venues such as theatres or restaurants that do not use the system can host a maximum of 50 people. If they opt to use the system, they can host as many people as they can accommodate if people are 1.5 metres from one another while seated. Events where guests have an assigned seat, whether indoor or outdoors, are also allowed again. However, these events must take account of local rules and requirements, such as permits.” "The fourth step of the reopening plan is now planned for 30 June."

Reservations can be made for up to 4 people. This limit does not apply to children under 13 and people who are part of the same household. The maximum number of visitors in one space or room is 50, at a distance of 1.5 metres apart.” "The fourth step of the reopening plan is now planned for 30 June."

description: January 31, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "primary schools and childcare centres for children aged 0 to 4 will reopen from 8 February." Social distancing (1.5 metres), mask-wearing and contact reduction apply. Children groups with positive cases will be quarantined. description: December 1, 2020: The Government of the Netherlands announced that “as of 1 December 2020, everyone aged 13 and over must wear a face mask in settings in which they are mandatory,” namely “all indoor public spaces and covered areas. This includes educational institutions, public transport and locations where contact-based professions are carried out, as well as shops, town halls and train stations.” “Always stay 1.5 metres away from other people, even if you are wearing a face mask.” “Keep your mask on wherever it is mandatory to do so, even if there are no other people around.” “Use face masks made for use by the general public. The use of transparent face shields instead of a face mask is not permitted.” “You can remove your face mask indoors once you are seated in an assigned seat, such as in a theatre. When you leave your seat, you must put your mask back on. This does not apply to public transport; you must wear your mask at all times while travelling by train, bus, tram or metro.” “Face masks are not mandatory in private buildings that are not freely accessible to the public.” “If you do not wear a face mask in a place where you must wear one, you may be fined.” UPDATE: June 18, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "step 4 of the reopening plan can be taken and that more restrictions than planned can be relaxed" from June 26, 2021. In this regard, "the requirement to wear a face mask will no longer apply in most situations. It will continue to apply only in situations where staying 1.5 apart is impossible.” Thus, this policy ends on June 25, 2021.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries

description: May 28, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the third step of its staggered reopening plan, starting on June 5, 2021. In this regard, it is implied that "you may not drink alcohol or have it on your person in public spaces" between 10pm and 6am (previously it was from 8pm until 7am). UPDATE: June 18, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "step 4 of the reopening plan can be taken and that more restrictions than planned can be relaxed" from June 26, 2021. In this regard, "the ban on drinking alcohol or having it on your person in public spaces after 22.00 will also be lifted."

description: June 18, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "step 4 of the reopening plan can be taken and that more restrictions than planned can be relaxed" from June 26, 2021. In this regard, "the recommendation to work from home unless this is not possible will change. From 26 June employees who currently work from home can, in consultation with their employer, work up to half of their hours at the office. People must stay 1.5 metres apart in offices at all times, including in lifts and cafeterias. The government is calling on people to travel to work outside peak hours as far as possible." "In mid-August [August 13, 2021] the government will decide how and when the final step of the reopening plan can be taken."

description: April 20, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the first step of its staggered reopening plan. In this regard, “as of Monday 26 April, students at universities and HBO institutions will again be able to attend classes at their educational institution". "Higher professional education institutions (HBO) and universities are partially open. They are still mainly offering remote and online learning. Each student can attend in-person classes approximately one day per week". "Students can attend their [...] university in person for practical training, tests and exams. Vulnerable [...] students can also be offered support on site at their school [or] institution". The second step of the reopening plan will be announced on May 11, 2021. UPDATE: June 18, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "step 4 of the reopening plan can be taken and that more restrictions than planned can be relaxed" from June 26, 2021. No relaxations are announced for "higher professional education institutions (HBO) and universities", thus confirming this policy until further reevaluation.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date

target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries

description: July 9, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "extra measures are necessary this summer." In this regard, the following measures will take effect from 06.00 on the morning of July 10, 2021 and remain in place until August 13, 2021: "Restaurants and bars may remain open provided all visitors have assigned seats that are placed 1.5 metres apart. All restaurants and bars must be closed from midnight until 06.00. Entertainment in the form of live performances and loud music is prohibited." "The coronavirus entry pass scheme, which granted an exemption from the 1.5 metre distancing rule, will be suspended for restaurants and bars until 13 August."

Pupils do not need to stay 1.5 metres apart and whole classes can attend in-person lessons at the same time. Pupils must stay 1.5 metres away from staff. In this regard, the following measures will take effect from 06.00 on the morning of July 10, 2021 and remain in place until August 13, 2021: "Restaurants and bars may remain open provided all visitors have assigned seats that are placed 1.5 metres apart. All restaurants and bars must be closed from midnight until 06.00. Entertainment in the form of live performances and loud music is prohibited." "The coronavirus entry pass scheme, which granted an exemption from the 1.5 metre distancing rule, will be suspended for restaurants and bars until 13 August." UPDATE: August 13, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "measures will be extended until 19 September inclusive." On September 17, 2021, "the government will assess whether it is possible to take the next step." In this regard, "in restaurants, bars and cafés, guests must have an assigned seat and these establishments must still close at midnight. Live and screened entertainment is not permitted."
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart at Restaurants
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health

description: April 20, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced the first step of its staggered reopening plan. In this regard, “as of Monday 26 April, students at universities and HBO institutions will again be able to attend classes at their educational institution". "Higher professional education institutions (HBO) and universities are partially open. They are still mainly offering remote and online learning. Each student can attend in-person classes approximately one day per week". "Students can attend their [...] university in person for practical training, tests and exams. Vulnerable [...] students can also be offered support on site at their school [or] institution". The second step of the reopening plan will be announced on May 11, 2021. UPDATE: August 13, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced new rules for higher education settings starting on August 30, 2021, setting the end date for this policy on August 29, 2021.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart at Higher education institutions (i.e. degree granting institutions)
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries
enforcer: National Government,Ministry/Department of Health,Ministry/Department of Justice,Ministry/Department of Education

description: July 9, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that extra measures are necessary during summer. New provisions will take effect from 6am on July 10, 2021 and remain in place until August 13, 2021. In this regard, "Secondary schools are open. Pupils do not need to stay 1.5 metres apart and whole classes can attend in-person lessons at the same time. Pupils must stay 1.5 metres away from staff. All other coronavirus measures for secondary schools still apply. Pupils and staff can take a self-test at home twice a week as a precaution. At schools and institutions a facemask must be worn in the corridor and when moving around. It can be taken off once the person is seated or standing at their allocated place.” UPDATE: August 13, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "measures will be extended until 19 September inclusive". On September 17, 2021, "the government will assess whether it is possible to take the next step". In this regard, "Secondary schools are open. Certain conditions apply.”
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date
type_sub_cat: Keeping a distance of at least 6 feet or 1.5 meters apart at Secondary Schools (generally for children ages 10 to 18)
target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries

description: June 18, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "step 4 of the reopening plan can be taken and that more restrictions than planned can be relaxed" from June 26, 2021. In this regard, "the requirement to wear a face mask will no longer apply in most situations,” including in primary schools and childcare centres for children aged 0 to 4, which reopened on February 8, 2021. Social distancing (1.5 metres) and contact reduction still apply. Children groups with positive cases will be quarantined. "In mid-August [August 13, 2021] the government will decide how and when the final step of the reopening plan can be taken." UPDATE: August 13, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced that "measures will be extended until 19 September inclusive." On September 17, 2021, "the government will assess whether it is possible to take the next step." This policy concerning childcare and primary schools is thus extended until at least September 19, 2021.
date_end_spec: The policy has a clear end date

target_geog_level: One or more countries, but not all countries

description: August 13, 2021: The Government of the Netherlands announced new rules for higher education settings starting on August 30, 2021. In this regard, “In the new academic year, students can attend onsite teaching at […] HBOs and universities. The 1.5 metre rule will no longer apply here. There will, however, be a number of additional conditions in place to ensure on-site learning can take place in a responsible way. This includes a maximum group size of 75 people and the use of facemasks outside lessons and lectures. Preventative self-testing is still strongly advised”.
